### Event Handling

React events are named using camelCase and passed as JSX attributes. They are synthetic events wrapping native browser events for cross-browser consistency.

---

### Basic Event Handlers

```jsx
function Button() {
  function handleClick(event) {
    console.log('Button clicked', event);
  }

  return <button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</button>;
}
```

### Event Object

React's synthetic event provides the same interface as native events but works consistently across browsers.

```jsx
function Input() {
  const handleChange = (e) => {
    console.log(e.target.value);
  };
  return <input onChange={handleChange} />;
}
```

### Common Events

| Event | Fires When |
|-------|-----------|
| `onClick` | Element is clicked |
| `onChange` | Input value changes |
| `onSubmit` | Form is submitted |
| `onKeyDown` | Key is pressed |
| `onFocus` | Element gains focus |
| `onBlur` | Element loses focus |
| `onMouseEnter` | Mouse enters element |
| `onMouseLeave` | Mouse leaves element |

### Passing Arguments

```jsx
<button onClick={() => handleDelete(id)}>Delete</button>
<button onClick={(e) => handleClick(id, e)}>Click</button>
```

> **Key Point:** Do not call the function in the JSX attribute. Pass a reference to the function or use an arrow function. Avoid inline arrow functions in performance-critical lists.

codeExample:
function Form() {
  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log('Form submitted');
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type="text" placeholder="Name" />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
